bug.short_desc: Make clean does not clean out files created during build process

long_desc.thetext: Please see attached the logs of a build attempt with origin/master at 7696653fa0fbed91f9cfd1f715b4ecb14858bfc4 (after merge of dev/automake)
Created an attachment (id=1476) build log of origin/master

(In reply to comment #1) > Created an attachment (id=1476) [details] > build log of origin/master
stringlist_t was removed from sieve.y (commit d0568654e557633a5 "Replace stringlist_t with strarray_t") and on my system, sieve.y does not contain stringlist_t.
I cannot reproduce the problem.
Update title of the bug to reflect what we've learned so far.
A `git clean -d -f -x` seems to help, but doesn't resolve the actual problem, IMO.

"make clean" is not supposed to delete sieve/sieve.c, but "make maintainer-clean" . The idea is, that sieve/sieve.c is generated from sieve/sieve.y by the maintainer, and not by the person who downloads the cyrus-imapd-...tar.gz file, who does not need to have yacc/bison in order to compile cyrus-imapd.
Most probably on your system sieve/sieve.c was for some reason newer than sieve/sieve.y and was therefore not regenerated, and still contains stringlist_t from an old sieve.y .

(In reply to comment #6) > "make clean" is not supposed to delete sieve/sieve.c, but "make > maintainer-clean" . The idea is, that sieve/sieve.c is generated from > sieve/sieve.y by the maintainer, and not by the person who downloads the > cyrus-imapd-...tar.gz file, who does not need to have yacc/bison in order to > compile cyrus-imapd. > > Most probably on your system sieve/sieve.c was for some reason newer than > sieve/sieve.y and was therefore not regenerated, and still contains > stringlist_t from an old sieve.y .
Now this gets confusing. As opposed to imap/rfc822_header.c, we do not distribute sieve/sieve.c through GIT.
Please require yacc/bison during ./configure and include the relevant files in 'make clean'.
FWIW this was also broken before we switched to automake; I've experienced this issue switching between modern and older branches.

"make" generates following files, if they do not exist:
xversion.h
cunit/ registers.h default.cunit
imap/ imap_err.[ch], lmtpstats.[ch], mupdate_err.[ch], nntp_err.[ch], pushstats.[ch], rfc822_header.[ch]
lib/ chartable.c, imapopts.]ch]
man/ cyradm.1, imapd.conf.5, sieveshell.1, sieveshell.1.html
sieve/ addr.[ch], addr-lex.c, sieve_err.[ch], sieve.[ch], sieve-lex.c
All of them are deleted with "make maintainer-clean" (see Automake manual, Nodes "clean" (What gets cleaned) and "Standard Targets" (Standard Targets for users)).
Which of these files shall be managed by git?
Which of these files shall be included in the tarball?
If the addr.[ch] and sieve.[ch] files are contained in the tarball, then the one who extracts the files from the tarball, does not need Yacc/Bison in order to compile the source.

(In reply to comment #9) > Which of these files shall be managed by git? >
The rule of thumb is, files generated during 'make' should not be managed by git, like files generated by './configure' are not.
> Which of these files shall be included in the tarball? > > If the addr.[ch] and sieve.[ch] files are contained in the tarball, then the > one who extracts the files from the tarball, does not need Yacc/Bison in order > to compile the source.
Yet if yacc/bison is available, regardless of whether the files generated exist, they could be re-generated and they probably should (like imap/rfc822_header.c is re-generated if gperf is available).

>> Which of these files shall be managed by git? > The rule of thumb is, files generated during 'make' should not be managed by git, like files generated by './configure' are not.
Please delete from git imap/rfc822_header.[ch]
>> If the addr.[ch] and sieve.[ch] files are contained in the tarball, then the >> one who extracts the files from the tarball, does not need Yacc/Bison in order >> to compile the source. > >Yet if yacc/bison is available, regardless of whether the files generated >exist, they could be re-generated and they probably should (like >imap/rfc822_header.c is re-generated if gperf is available).
If bison or flex are detected by ./configure and sieve/sieve(-lex).c is outdated, /make/ will update it. It the files are up to date, they are not (should not be) regenerated.
Anyway, which of the mentioned files shall be packed by "make dist" in the tarball?

(In reply to comment #11) > >> Which of these files shall be managed by git? > > The rule of thumb is, files generated during 'make' should not be managed by > git, like files generated by './configure' are not. > > Please delete from git imap/rfc822_header.[ch] >
If we do, we have to require gperf in ./configure.
> >> If the addr.[ch] and sieve.[ch] files are contained in the tarball, then the > >> one who extracts the files from the tarball, does not need Yacc/Bison in order > >> to compile the source. > > > >Yet if yacc/bison is available, regardless of whether the files generated > >exist, they could be re-generated and they probably should (like > >imap/rfc822_header.c is re-generated if gperf is available). > > If bison or flex are detected by ./configure and sieve/sieve(-lex).c is > outdated, /make/ will update it. It the files are up to date, they are not > (should not be) regenerated. >
Note that not even a make -B (always-make) re-generates the files. I think it is best to just require gperf and bison during ./configure and include these files in 'make clean' - the 'maintainer' targets can then go away - it's the most straightforward approach.
> Anyway, which of the mentioned files shall be packed by "make dist" in the > tarball?
If we just require gperf and bison during ./configure, none of the aforementioned files needs to be in the 'make dist' tarball, right?

The tarball created by "make dist" includes now imap/rfc822_header.c, imap/rfc822_header.h, imap/rfc822_header.st, sieve/addr.c, sieve/addr.c, sieve/addr.y, sieve/addr-lex.c, sieve/addr-lex.l, sieve/sieve.c sieve/sieve.h, sieve/sieve.y, sieve/sieve-lex.c, sieve/sieve-lex.l and ./configure checks for lex and yacc.
So, if somebody updates the .y or .l or .st files, and has yacc/lex/gperf, the corresponsing .c targets will be updates. If the one unpacking the .tar file does not change the .l or .y files, she does not need flex and yacc to compile cyrus-imapd. I do not see why must yacc/lex be required.
The sieve.c and sieve.h files are included even in cyrus-imapd-2.4.15.tar.gz .
Anyway, we can move the discussion to cyrus-devel to reach a consensus if sieve.h and sieve.c shall be included in the tarball created by "make dist" (and which other files).
I put now in the tarball also doc/master.png and doc/netnews.png .
I still have to check how NOT to include the _err.c and _err.h files.

Can this bug get closed now?
"make distclean" deletes imap/*_err.[ch] .
After doing "make maintainer-clean", git clean -dfnx reports

I consider this issue as resolved now, in regards of deleting files on "make distclean" and "make maintainer-clean".
Upon "make dist", the files _err.c and _err.h are not included in the tarball.
bison/flex and gperf are not required for running ./configure && make, provided that the generated files (sieve/sieve.c, sieve/addr-lex.c, imap/rfc822_header.h, etc) are packaged by "make dist" (and they are included).
bison/flex are required for building the code from git, as are automake, autoconf and libtool.
gperf is not required for building the code from git, as the files generated by gperf, imap/rfc822.[ch] are in the repository.
